bib.title: Slow Neutron Inelastic Scattering Study of LightWater and Ice

free_txt: S(alpha,beta) and complementary data.

The scattered neutron energy in subentries 2-60 was
recalculated as E = beta * kT + En.
Battelle Rotating Crystal
Spectrometer (CRXS).
Time-of-flight (TOF) detectors located around
the sample in the horizontal plane recorded the TOF
spectra of scattered neutrons. Nine or ten TOF
detectors were arranged on flight paths of 1.0 or 1.5
m, at scattering angles from 15-165 degrees. A range
of incident neutron energies was used to provide high
resolution on scattered neutron energy over the
entire range of frequencies from below the hindered
rotational band to beyond the stretching vibrational
modes.
The samples of liquid water were contained between
two stretched, 0.025-cm-thick, high-strength anodized
aluminum alloy windows. The maximum bulge in these
samples was ~0.0025 cm. An H20 sample 8.9 cm wide by
11.4 cm high by 0.031 cm thick was used for all the
water measurements except at Eo=0.608 eV. The 0.608
eV scattering data were taken with a sample 7.6X
15.24X0.86 cm. The samples were inclined 45 degrees
to the incident beam direction. Transmissions in this
orientation were 0.915, 0.93, 0.935, and 0.825 for
initial energies of 0.1515, 0.304, 0.404, and 0.608
eV, respectively. Ice samples were made on a
0.158-cm-thick aluminum plate which was cooled by
conduction from the edges. Thin layers of water were
frozen onto this plate until the desired thickness
was reached. The final thickness of ice was adjusted
by scraping with a straight edge. Final dimensions of
the ice samples were 7.6 X 15.24 X ~0.038 cm. A
0.086-cm-thick sample was also used for one
experiment with E0=0.616 eV. Variability in the ice
layer thickness was ~lO% by this method of
manufacture. The ice samples were also inclined 45
degrees to the incident beam direction and sample
transmissions were 0.91 and 0.92 for E0=0.1515 and
0.304 eV, respectively. For E0=0.616 eV the
transmissions were 0.90 and 0.75.
